      <h1>Prevention strategies</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        The CSAP six strategies — the kinds of work prevention specialists
        actually do, and how each one looks when the target condition is
        gambling harm.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <p>
        Prevention is not one activity — it is a portfolio. The Center for
        Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP), part of the federal Substance Abuse
        and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA), organizes that
        portfolio into <strong>six strategy categories</strong>. These
        categories were established in 1981 under the Substance Abuse
        Prevention and Treatment (SAPT) Block Grant and remain the common
        language prevention professionals use to plan, fund, and report their
        work (Prevention Technology Transfer Center Network, n.d.).
      </p>
      <p>
        The six strategies were built for substance misuse, but they apply
        cleanly to problem gambling. A complete gambling prevention plan uses
        several of them at once, because no single strategy reaches everyone
        or addresses every driver of gambling-related harm. CSAP's own
        guidance is that a comprehensive approach drawing on as many of the
        six as fit the local need works best.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two clarifications before the strategies themselves. First, a
        <em>strategy</em> is a category of activity, not a program — "Stacked
        Deck" is a program; the strategy it belongs to is education. Second,
        the six strategies describe <em>what you do</em>. A second framework,
        the Institute of Medicine's intervention spectrum, describes <em>who
        you reach</em>. Practitioners plan best when they hold both axes at
        once — so we start there.
      </p>

      <h2>The IOM intervention spectrum: who prevention reaches</h2>
      <p>
        In 1994, the Institute of Medicine (IOM) published a framework that
        reorganized how the field thinks about prevention. Rather than the
        older primary/secondary/tertiary model, the IOM reserved the word
        <em>prevention</em> for interventions that occur <strong>before the
        onset of a disorder</strong>, and divided preventive interventions
        into three types based on the population reached (Institute of
        Medicine, 1994):
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Universal prevention</strong> — directed at a general
          population or group that has not been identified by individual
          risk. Desirable for everyone in the group, and most appropriate
          when cost per person is low and the intervention carries little
          risk. <em>Gambling example:</em> a statewide public-awareness
          campaign on the odds and house edge during Problem Gambling
          Awareness Month; age limits on lottery and sports-betting products.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Selective prevention</strong> — directed at subgroups whose
          risk of developing the disorder is significantly higher than
          average, identified by biological, psychological, or social risk
          factors. <em>Gambling example:</em> programming for college
          athletes and sports-betting-saturated campuses, for young men (a
          higher-prevalence group), or for people in substance-use recovery,
          among whom gambling problems are more common.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Indicated prevention</strong> — directed at high-risk
          individuals showing early, detectable signs that foreshadow a
          disorder but who do not yet meet diagnostic criteria. <em>Gambling
          example:</em> a brief screen that flags someone betting more than
          intended, followed by early skill-building and a referral pathway —
          before the pattern meets the threshold for gambling disorder.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The IOM placed prevention at one end of a continuum that also includes
        treatment and maintenance (Institute of Medicine, 1994). For gambling
        work, the line between prevention and treatment can blur, and one of
        the six strategies (problem identification and referral) sits right
        at that boundary — a point we return to below.
      </p>
      <p>
        A useful way to read the rest of this page: the <strong>six CSAP
        strategies are the "what,"</strong> and the <strong>IOM spectrum is
        the "who."</strong> A given strategy can operate at any level of the
        spectrum. Information dissemination is usually universal; a
        coping-skills curriculum delivered to a high-risk subgroup is
        selective; a screen-and-refer process is often indicated.
      </p>

      <h2>The six CSAP strategies, applied to problem gambling</h2>
      <p>
        CSAP's definitions are paraphrased below from the Center for Substance
        Abuse Prevention's combined strategy list (CSAP, 2015). Each is
        followed by its translation to gambling prevention.
      </p>

      <h3>1. Information dissemination</h3>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          CSAP defines this strategy as building awareness and knowledge about
          the nature, extent, and effects of substance use and addiction on
          individuals, families, and communities, and as making people aware
          of available prevention services. It is characterized as
          <strong>one-way communication</strong> — print and electronic media,
          public service announcements, speaking engagements, resource
          directories, clearinghouses, and health fairs (CSAP, 2015).
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong>For problem gambling</strong>, this is the most visible
        strategy and the easiest to do — and the easiest to do superficially.
        Done well, it corrects the specific false beliefs that drive gambling
        harm:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Accurate odds, house edge, and randomness messaging.</strong>
          Information dissemination is the vehicle for correcting gambling
          fallacies: the gambler's fallacy (that a run of losses makes a win
          "due"), the belief that skill influences chance-based games, and
          the illusion of control. Messaging that explains how the house edge
          works and that each outcome is independent targets exactly the
          cognitions that distinguish people with gambling problems.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Problem Gambling Awareness Month (PGAM).</strong> Held every
          March, PGAM is a nationwide grassroots campaign to increase public
          awareness of problem gambling and the availability of prevention,
          treatment, and recovery services (NCPG, PGAM, n.d.). NCPG publishes
          a free annual PGAM toolkit (FAQs, social-media best practices, a
          press-release template) that practitioners can localize.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Myth-busting.</strong> Common myths — that gambling is a
          reliable way to make money, that "real" gamblers always lose
          everything, that problem gambling only affects certain kinds of
          people — can be addressed directly through factual, non-stigmatizing
          content.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The limit of this strategy is well established: awareness messaging
        reliably moves knowledge and attitudes, but knowledge change alone
        does not reliably change behavior. That is why information
        dissemination is a necessary but not sufficient part of a plan — a
        finding echoed in the school-based gambling-education literature
        discussed under strategy 2 (Calado et al., 2020).
      </p>

      <h3>2. Education / prevention education</h3>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          CSAP distinguishes the education strategy from information
          dissemination by its reliance on <strong>two-way communication</strong>
          — interaction between facilitator and participants is the basis of
          its activities — and by its aim to "improve critical life and
          social skills," including decision-making, refusal skills, critical
          analysis, and systematic judgment. It need not happen in a
          classroom (CSAP, 2015).
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong>For problem gambling</strong>, this is where youth and
        skill-building work lives:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Stacked Deck</strong> is the most-cited evidence-informed,
          school-based gambling prevention curriculum. It is a set of five to
          six interactive lessons covering the history of gambling, the true
          odds and house edge, gambling fallacies, the signs and risk
          factors for problem gambling, and decision-making and
          problem-solving skills (Williams, Wood, &amp; Currie, 2010). In its
          original controlled evaluation — 949 grade 9–12 students across 10
          program schools compared with control schools in southern Alberta
          — Stacked Deck improved gambling knowledge, reduced gambling
          fallacies and shifted attitudes, and was associated with decreases
          in the frequency of problem gambling and in hours spent gambling.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The math of gambling and coping/decision-making skills.</strong>
          Beyond a single curriculum, the education strategy supports
          teaching the probability concepts behind games of chance and the
          coping, refusal, and decision-making skills that help young people
          manage risk.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        An honest note for planners: across the school-based gambling
        prevention literature, programs <strong>consistently improve
        knowledge and correct misconceptions</strong>, but their effect on
        <strong>actual gambling behavior is mixed and less well established</strong>
        — researchers describe a lack of transference of knowledge into
        behavior change in some studies (Calado et al., 2020). This is a
        reason to pair education with environmental strategies rather than
        rely on it alone.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Alternative activities (positive alternatives)</h3>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          CSAP describes this strategy as giving target populations the chance
          to participate in activities that exclude substance use. The
          assumption is that constructive, healthy activities offset the
          attractions otherwise filled by substances and minimize the need to
          use them. Examples include substance-free social and recreational
          events, community drop-in centers, structured recreation, and
          youth/adult leadership activities (CSAP, 2015).
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong>For problem gambling</strong>, the same logic applies:
        structured, engaging programming that competes for the time, social
        connection, and stimulation that gambling can otherwise provide.
        Practical applications include youth recreation, sports, arts, and
        leadership programming during high-exposure periods (for example,
        around major sporting events now saturated with betting advertising),
        and community spaces that give adolescents and young adults
        appealing alternatives to social-casino apps and online betting.
        Note of caution: this is the strategy with the <strong>thinnest
        gambling-specific evidence base</strong>. The underlying theory is
        borrowed largely from substance-use prevention; alternative
        activities are best treated as a complement to other strategies
        rather than a stand-alone solution.
      </p>

      <h3>4. Problem identification and referral</h3>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          CSAP defines this strategy as identifying people who have already
          used in age-inappropriate ways and assessing whether their behavior
          can be reversed through education — explicitly aimed at <strong>behavioral
          change, not therapy</strong>, and explicitly <em>not</em> including
          treatment assessment (CSAP, 2015).
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        This is the strategy that generates the most confusion in the field
        precisely because it sits at the prevention–treatment boundary
        (CSAP, 2015).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>For problem gambling</strong>, this is brief screening plus a
        warm referral — <em>not</em> treatment:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Brief screens.</strong> The <strong>Brief Biosocial
          Gambling Screen (BBGS)</strong> is a three-question instrument
          developed by researchers at the Division on Addiction, Cambridge
          Health Alliance (a Harvard Medical School teaching affiliate), to
          help a person decide whether to seek a more formal evaluation
          (International Center for Responsible Gaming, n.d.; Gebauer,
          LaBrie, &amp; Shaffer, 2010). It has strong reported psychometrics
          for identifying gambling disorder (Dowling et al., 2018). The
          <strong>Lie/Bet</strong> questionnaire is a widely used two-item
          screen asking about needing to bet more over time and about lying
          to people close to the person about how much they gamble; in
          comparative testing, two-item screens detect problem gambling
          adequately but are less sensitive to lower-risk gambling (Dowling
          et al., 2018). NCPG and the Division on Addiction promote
          screening through an annual <strong>Gambling Disorder Screening
          Day</strong> each March, with a free toolkit (NCPG, n.d.).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Warm referral.</strong> When a screen flags concern, the
          prevention role is to connect the person to help — for example,
          to the <strong>National Problem Gambling Helpline</strong> at
          <a href="tel:18006973738">1-800-MY-RESET (1-800-697-3738)</a>,
          available 24/7 and a source of support and referrals to local
          resources (NCPG, n.d.). Where a person is in crisis, <a
          href="tel:988">988</a> (the 988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline;
          call, text, or chat 988) is the appropriate route.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The boundary matters operationally as well as conceptually: per
        SAMHSA guidance reflected in CSAP's strategy list, primary-prevention
        set-aside funds <strong>cannot</strong> be used to fund screening,
        brief intervention, and referral to treatment (SBIRT) or treatment
        assessment (CSAP, 2015). Screening as identification-and-referral is
        prevention; diagnosis and treatment are not.
      </p>

      <h3>5. Community-based process</h3>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          CSAP describes this strategy as building the community's capacity
          to deliver prevention more effectively — through organizing,
          planning, interagency collaboration, coalition building, and
          networking (CSAP, 2015). It aligns closely with the assessment,
          capacity, planning, and evaluation steps of the Strategic
          Prevention Framework.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong>For problem gambling</strong>, community-based process is how
        a community develops the <em>infrastructure</em> to address gambling
        at all — building or expanding a coalition to include the sectors
        that touch gambling (schools, behavioral health, the faith
        community, the recovery community, regulators, and, where
        appropriate, the gambling industry), training that coalition's
        members, and coordinating across agencies that have historically
        treated gambling as no one's specific responsibility. The Community
        Tool Box and CADCA provide widely used, free guidance on coalition
        development and the multi-sector model that this strategy depends
        on. Because gambling prevention is newer and less funded than
        substance-use prevention in most jurisdictions, this strategy is
        often the prerequisite that makes the other five possible.
        Coalition development is covered in depth on the companion <a
        href="/understand-prevention/coalitions">Coalitions</a> page.
      </p>

      <h3>6. Environmental strategies</h3>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          CSAP describes environmental strategies as identifying,
          establishing, or changing community standards, codes, and
          attitudes — through creation, modification, passage, and
          enforcement of policy, plus media strategies that change norms.
          Results can be wide-ranging and sustained, although specific
          recipients are not identified (CSAP, 2015).
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong>For problem gambling, this is often the highest-leverage
        strategy</strong> — and the one most distinctive to gambling, because
        commercial gambling products and their marketing are environmental
        features that shape harm at the population level. Applications include:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Age and access limits</strong> — minimum age requirements
          for lottery, casino, and sports-betting products, and enforcement
          of them.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Advertising and marketing restrictions</strong> — limits on
          the volume, placement, and content of gambling advertising,
          especially around youth-attended events and during sports
          broadcasts; restrictions on inducements such as "risk-free" bet
          promotions.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Self-exclusion programs</strong> — voluntary programs
          through which a person bars themselves from venues or online
          platforms. The evidence is not comprehensive, but available
          findings suggest self-exclusion confers meaningful benefit for
          people experiencing gambling problems (Gainsbury, 2014).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Responsible-gambling product features</strong> — deposit,
          loss, and time limits; mandatory break ("reality-check") prompts;
          and <strong>default protections</strong> built into the product.
          The evidence here is mixed and is a live research area: voluntary
          limit-setting and prompts can reduce gambling intensity for some
          users in the near term, but several systematic reviews have not
          found clear evidence that voluntary monetary pre-commitment
          reliably prevents people from spending more than intended, and
          adherence falls among higher-risk users without enforcement
          (Ladouceur et al., 2017). The design distinction matters:
          mandatory and default-on protections tend to reach the people who
          most need them; voluntary, opt-in features tend not to.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Lottery and sports-betting policy</strong> — the rules
          governing how state lotteries and newly legal sports-betting
          markets operate, advertise, and fund problem-gambling services.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Because these strategies change the environment for everyone, they
        are inherently <strong>universal</strong> on the IOM spectrum and do
        not depend on identifying or motivating individuals — which is
        precisely why they are the population-level workhorse of gambling
        prevention.
      </p>

      <h2>Individual-level vs. environmental/population-level change</h2>
      <p>
        The six strategies split along a fault line worth naming explicitly.
        <strong>Information dissemination, education, alternative
        activities, and problem identification &amp; referral</strong>
        mostly work at the <strong>individual level</strong> — they aim to
        change what a person knows, can do, or decides. <strong>Community-based
        process and, especially, environmental strategies</strong> work at
        the <strong>population level</strong> — they change the conditions
        that everyone is exposed to.
      </p>
      <p>
        For gambling, the population-level lens is essential. Much of the
        causal action in modern gambling harm is in the <strong>design of
        the product and the saturation of its marketing</strong> — the speed
        and structure of electronic gaming machines, the always-available
        nature of mobile betting, in-play microbetting, and the volume of
        advertising — none of which an individual-skills approach can fully
        offset. The same logic public health applies to tobacco and alcohol
        holds here: individual education matters, but the largest and most
        durable reductions in population harm have historically come from
        environmental change (pricing, availability, marketing limits,
        defaults). A sound plan includes individual-level strategies
        <em>and</em> environmental ones, with realistic expectations: a
        youth curriculum and an awareness campaign will not, by themselves,
        counteract a high-exposure environment.
      </p>

      <h2>An honest note on the evidence base</h2>
      <p>
        The CSAP strategies and the IOM spectrum were built for substance
        misuse and are being extended to gambling. That extension is sound
        in principle, but the gambling-specific evidence is uneven, and
        practitioners should plan and evaluate with that in mind:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Information dissemination and education</strong> reliably
          improve gambling knowledge and correct misconceptions; their effect
          on actual gambling behavior is less consistent (Calado et al.,
          2020; Williams, Wood, &amp; Currie, 2010).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Alternative activities</strong> rest largely on theory
          borrowed from substance-use prevention, with limited gambling-specific
          outcome evidence.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Problem identification &amp; referral</strong> has
          well-validated brief screening tools (BBGS, Lie/Bet) (Dowling et
          al., 2018; Gebauer, LaBrie, &amp; Shaffer, 2010), but the
          downstream impact of screen-and-refer programs on population
          outcomes is less studied.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Environmental strategies</strong> are theoretically the
          highest-leverage approach, and self-exclusion shows promise, but
          the evidence for several voluntary responsible-gambling features
          (especially voluntary pre-commitment limits) is mixed (Gainsbury,
          2014; Ladouceur et al., 2017).
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The practical takeaway: layer the strategies, prioritize
        environmental and population-level change where you can influence
        it, and build evaluation into the work so the gambling-specific
        evidence base continues to grow.
      </p>

